text: In its efforts to procure supplies to fight the coronavirus, Britain has awarded thousands of contracts worth billions of dollars. Much of that money has gone to politically connected companies, a New York Times analysis found. https://t.co/5tEO7yZQlY

name: nytimes
text: We analyzed a large segment of the spending spree ‚Äî roughly 1,200 contracts worth nearly $22 billion. About $11 billion went to firms either run by friends and associates of Conservative Party politicians, or with no experience or a history of controversy. https://t.co/MU5Js60QJi https://t.co/88RGfkAbgb

name: nytimes
text: The suppliers we spoke to denied wrongdoing, and there‚Äôs no evidence that government officials engaged in illegal conduct. But there is ample evidence of cronyism, waste and poor due diligence. https://t.co/MU5Js60QJi

name: nytimes
text: About $5 billion went to politically connected companies, including hundreds of millions to several where Britain‚Äôs PPE czar has financial interests or personal connections. A secretive ‚ÄúVIP lane‚Äù gave priority to firms with political ties. https://t.co/MU5Js60QJi https://t.co/OPPaRlMBeM

name: nytimes
text: About $6 billion went to companies with no experience in supplying medical PPE ‚Äî fashion designers, investment firms, pest controllers and jewelers. In some cases they delivered unusable goods. https://t.co/MU5Js60QJi https://t.co/1HNaPEtfT9

name: nytimes
text: More than $5 billion was awarded to companies with a history of controversy, from tax evasion and fraud to corruption and human rights abuses. https://t.co/MU5Js60QJi https://t.co/IlQU1zgA9t

name: nytimes

name: nytimes
text:
Air pollution can be deadly in India, where it contributed to the deaths of more people last year than any other risk factor. 

We followed two children from different backgrounds in New Delhi and measured their exposure to pollution. 
https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O

name: nytimes
text:
Monu, 13, and Aamya, 11, breathe some of the most polluted air in the world, but only Aamya's family can afford air purifiers.

Over the course of one day, Monu was exposed to about four times as much PM 2.5 ‚Äî a measure of pollution ‚Äî  as Aamya. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/83vJEe8Q0M

name: nytimes
text: The difference in their exposure is clear as soon as they wake up. Monu lifts his mosquito net and crawls out of bed onto a dirt floor. Outside, his mom cooks over an open fire. A few miles away, Aamya‚Äôs mom wakes her; an air purifier purrs in the hallway. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/sDlm3a8IG9

name: nytimes
text:
Homes in upper-middle class neighborhoods in New Delhi with well-fitted windows and air purifiers tend to have cleaner air than homes in less affluent areas.

Monu and Aamya live just miles apart, but their daily lives illustrate the disparity. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/bjcwbAbbQ0

name: nytimes
text:
Working with researchers from ILK Labs last year, New York Times journalists tracked how much air pollution Aamya and Monu were exposed to over the course of a day.

We could see the differences just from the filters on their pollution monitors. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/dLTPvNZPIv

name: nytimes
text:
Their schools provide widely different levels of protection.

Aamya attends a private school known for its efforts to insulate students from air pollution.

Monu‚Äôs school is free ‚Äî but it has no walls or doors. The classroom air is the same as outside. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/QNAUw2wr8d

name: nytimes
text: At Monu‚Äôs school, which is built under a bridge, he is exposed to more than three times the pollution in his classroom than Aamya, whose school has air purifiers in every room. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/XOTlMhkYcG

name: nytimes
text:
When Monu does his homework, his mom cooks over a fire, filling the air with smoke. At Aamya‚Äôs home, a servant cooks in another room.

Pollution around Aamya rose, but not as much as for Monu, who was exposed to some of the highest levels of the day. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/b7m0n7CwRR

name: nytimes
text:
The pollution on the day we measured Monu and Aamya's air quality was bad, but it was four times higher on Delhi's worst day last year.

Still, the data shows how Monu is consistently exposed to more pollution. https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O https://t.co/7h8Vqm9dPu

name: nytimes
text: We used four different air monitors to collect this data. Our main tool was an AirBeam 2, which we connected to a small, battery-powered @Raspberry_Pi computer running customized open-source software for collecting data. Read more on our methodology: https://t.co/Q6YDk0Atz4

name: nytimes
text:
There is no single cause of India‚Äôs pollution, and no single solution. The government has not made air pollution as high a priority as rapid economic growth.

Clean-air activists say most people have no idea about how bad pollution really is. 

Read more: https://t.co/E2agHWgT8O
